Year = {{2019}},
Volume = {{8}},
Number = {{4}},
Month = {{APR}},
Abstract = {{Transport decision-making problems are typically spatially based and
   involve a set of feasible alternatives with multiple evaluation
   criteria. Besides, transport decisions affect citizens' quality of life,
   as well as specific interests of general stakeholders (e.g., transport
   companies), thus needing a participatory approach to decision-making.
   Geographic Information Systems (GIS) have the ability to visualize
   spatial data and represent the impact of location based transport
   alternatives, thus helping experts to conduct robust assessments.
   Moreover, with the recent diffusion of Volunteered Geographic
   Information (VGI) and development of Public Participatory GIS (PPGIS)
   platforms, the process can be enhanced thanks to the collection of a
   large amount of updated spatial data and the achievement of an active
   community participation. In this study, we provide an overview based on
   a structured literature review of the use of VGI and PPGIS in transport
   studies, exploring the fields of application, role played by GIS, level
   of public involvement and decision stage at which they are applied. From
   the overview's results, we propose a general framework for the
   evaluation of transport alternatives using GIS from a multiple
   stakeholder point of view; the main conclusion is the usefulness of the
   integration between Public Participation, GIS and quantitative
   evaluation methods, in particular Multi Criteria Decision Analysis, in
   order to foster technically sound and shared decisions.}},
